        <productionVolumeComment xml:lang="en">Estimated value. The global production volume is extrapolated from the European production volume based on reports from Cefic (European Chemical Industry Council), and the American Chemistry Council.  
According to Cefic (2016) the Global sales of chemicals in the year 2015 was 3 534 billion euros. The reported share of sales per regions are: EU28 14.7%; Other Europe (Switzerland, Norway, Turkey, Russia and Ukraine) 2.7%; NAFTA (US, Canada and Mexico) 16.5%; Latin America 3.8%; China 39.9%; Japan 3.9%; Republic of Korea 3.2%; India 2.2%; Rest of Asia 11.9%; Rest of the World 1.3%. Cefic also reports the US total sales, 518.7 billion euros of the global 3 534 billion euros (14.7%). The same share is reported from the American Chemistry Council (2016), according to this source the USA sales account for 15% of global sales for the year 2016. 
European production volume: This production volume represents an approximate estimation for Europe in 2002, derived from the production capacity of sodium chlorate in Western (700kt/yr) and Eastern Europe (100kt/yr). Based on literature, it can be assumed that around 89% of sodium chlorate produced is used in the pulp and paper industry for the production of chlorine dioxide, which accounts for more than 95% of the total chlorine dioxide production (ATSDR, 2004). 1.66 kg of sodium chlorate are used to produce 1 kg of chlorine dioxide (see exchanges).  Since no data were found for the global production this value was scaled accordingly.

Reference(s):
Cefic 2016. Facts and figures 2016 of the European chemical industry. Accessible at: http://www.cefic.org/Facts-and-Figures/Chemicals-Industry-Profile/ 
American Chemistry Council 2016. Outlook: U.S. Chemical Industry Continues to Outpace Industrial Output; Accounts for More Than One-Half of Construction Spending by Manufacturing Sector. Accessible at: https://www.americanchemistry.com/Media/PressReleasesTranscripts/ACC-news-releases/US-Chemical-Industry-Continues-to-Outpace-Industrial-Output.html. European Commission (EC), 2007, Reference Document on Best Available Techniques for the Manufacture of Large Volume Inorganic Chemicals - Solids and Others industry, August 2007; retrieved from http://eippcb.jrc.ec.europa.eu/reference/BREF/lvic-s_bref_0907.pdf, p 514; accessed 15.06.2017). Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry (ATSDR), 2004, Toxicological Profile for Chlorine Dioxide and Chlorite, Retrieved on 15 of June 2017 from: https://www.atsdr.cdc.gov/toxprofiles/tp160-c5.pdf. As it is based on production capacity rather than actual volumes this figure may be overestimated. </productionVolumeComment>
